4","1294":"1294","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1239":"1239","1349":"1349","1315":"1315","1313":"1313","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","1355":"1355","1307":"1307","1317":"1317","England":"England","Umberleigh, Devon, England":"Umberleigh, Devon, England","Sandhurst, Gloucestershire, England":"Sandhurst, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Wilington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of English   Wigginton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wigginton","meanings":["English (Leicestershire and Rutland): habitational name from any of several places called Wigginton, in Staffordshire, Oxfordshire, Hertfordshire, and North Yorkshire. The Staffordshire, Oxfordshire, and Hertfordshire placenames derive from the Old English personal name <i>Wicga</i> (genitive <i>Wicgan</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’ or the personal name <i>Wicga</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The North Yorkshire placename may derive from the Old Norse personal name <i>Víkingr</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of 